Almost every DevOps tool you use—Docker, Jenkins, Nginx, Apache, SSH, Kubernetes components—runs as a service managed by systemd.

Step 5 – Services & systemd
🎯 Learning Objectives

By the end of this step, you'll be able to:

Understand what a service is.
Learn what systemd is.
Start, stop, restart, and reload services.
Enable and disable services at boot.
Check service status.
Read service logs.
Create your own systemd service.
Troubleshoot service failures.
1. What is a Service?

A service (also called a daemon) is a program that runs in the background and waits to perform work.

Examples:

SSH Server → Allows remote login.
Nginx → Serves web pages.
Docker → Runs containers.
Jenkins → CI/CD automation.
Cron → Executes scheduled jobs.

Think of a service like an employee working continuously in the background instead of only when you open a program.

2. What is systemd?

systemd is the service manager used by most modern Linux distributions.

Its responsibilities include:

Starting services.
Stopping services.
Restarting services.
Managing boot order.
Tracking logs.
Restarting failed services (if configured).

Verify it's running:

ps -p 1

Expected output:

PID TTY      TIME CMD
1   ?        00:00:05 systemd

Interview Tip: PID 1 is usually the systemd process.

3. List Running Services
systemctl list-units --type=service

This displays active services.

4. Check Service Status

Example with SSH:

systemctl status ssh

Possible output:

Active: active (running)

If a service isn't running:

Active: inactive (dead)
5. Start a Service
sudo systemctl start nginx

Check its status:

systemctl status nginx
6. Stop a Service
sudo systemctl stop nginx
7. Restart a Service
sudo systemctl restart nginx

This is commonly used after changing configuration files.

8. Reload a Service
sudo systemctl reload nginx

Difference:

Restart → Stops and starts the service.
Reload → Applies configuration changes without a full restart (if the service supports it).
9. Enable a Service at Boot
sudo systemctl enable nginx

Now Nginx starts automatically when the server boots.

10. Disable Automatic Startup
sudo systemctl disable nginx
11. Check if a Service is Enabled
systemctl is-enabled nginx

Output:

enabled

or

disabled
12. Check if a Service is Active
systemctl is-active nginx

Output:

active

or

inactive
13. View Service Logs

systemd stores logs in the journal.

Show logs:

journalctl -u nginx

Latest logs first:

journalctl -u nginx -r

Follow logs in real time:

journalctl -u nginx -f

Exit with:

Ctrl + C
14. View Boot Logs
journalctl -b

Previous boot:

journalctl -b -1

Very useful when a server fails after reboot.

15. Create Your Own Service

Create a script:

mkdir -p ~/scripts
nano ~/scripts/hello.sh

Contents:

#!/bin/bash

while true
do
    echo "Hello DevOps $(date)" >> /tmp/hello.log
    sleep 10
done

Make it executable:

chmod +x ~/scripts/hello.sh

Create a service file:

sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/hello.service

Paste:

[Unit]
Description=Hello DevOps Service
After=network.target

[Service]
ExecStart=/home/<YOUR_USERNAME>/scripts/hello.sh
Restart=always

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target

Replace <YOUR_USERNAME> with your Linux username.

Reload systemd:

sudo systemctl daemon-reload

Start the service:

sudo systemctl start hello

Enable it:

sudo systemctl enable hello

Check status:

systemctl status hello

Verify the log file is being updated:

tail -f /tmp/hello.log
16. Common systemctl Commands
Command	Purpose
systemctl status	Show service status
systemctl start	Start a service
systemctl stop	Stop a service
systemctl restart	Restart a service
systemctl reload	Reload configuration
systemctl enable	Start at boot
systemctl disable	Don't start at boot
systemctl is-active	Check running state
systemctl is-enabled	Check boot state
systemctl daemon-reload	Reload service definitions
