💼 Real DevOps Scenario

Suppose your website is returning errors after a configuration change.

A common troubleshooting workflow is:

systemctl status nginx

If the service failed:

journalctl -u nginx -n 50

Fix the configuration, then:

sudo systemctl restart nginx

Finally, verify:

systemctl is-active nginx

This pattern applies not just to Nginx, but also to Docker, Jenkins, SSH, and many other services you'll manage as a DevOps engineer.

🎤 Interview Questions
What is a Linux service?
A Linux service is a program or process that runs in the background (daemon) to provide system or application functionality. Services often start automatically during system boot.
Examples:
SSH (sshd)
Nginx (nginx)
Docker (docker)


What is systemd?
systemd is the default system and service manager on most modern Linux distributions. It is responsible for:
Starting services during boot
Managing services
Handling dependencies
Logging (through journald)
Managing system states (targets)
Common commands:
sudo systemctl start nginx
sudo systemctl stop nginx
sudo systemctl restart nginx


Why is PID 1 important?
PID 1 is the first process started by the Linux kernel during boot.
On most modern Linux systems, PID 1 is systemd.
Its responsibilities include:
Starting system services
Managing child processes
Adopting orphaned processes
Coordinating system shutdown and reboot
To check PID 1:
ps -p 1
Example output:
PID TTY          TIME CMD
1   ?        00:00:02 systemd

What is the difference between restart and reload?
restart                               	    reload
Stops and starts the service.	            Reloads configuration without stopping the service.
Existing connections may be interrupted.	Existing connections usually continue.
Used after binary or major changes.	        Used after configuration changes.
sudo systemctl restart nginx                  sudo systemctl reload nginx


What does systemctl enable do?
systemctl enable configures a service to start automatically at boot by creating the necessary symbolic links.
Example:
sudo systemctl enable nginx
To enable and start immediately:
sudo systemctl enable --now nginx

How do you check whether a service is running?
systemctl status nginx
systemctl is-active nginx
Possible results:
active
inactive
failed


What is journalctl used for?
journalctl displays logs collected by the systemd journal.
Useful commands:
View all logs:journalctl
View logs for a specific service:
journalctl -u nginx
Show the latest logs:
journalctl -u nginx -n 20
Follow logs in real time:
journalctl -u nginx -f

Why do you run systemctl daemon-reload?
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
after:
Creating a new .service file
Modifying an existing .service file
It reloads the systemd configuration so it recognizes the changes

How do you configure a service to start automatically after reboot?
Enable the service:
sudo systemctl enable nginx
Or enable and start it immediately:
sudo systemctl enable --now nginx
Verify:
systemctl is-enabled nginx
Expected output:
enabled

How would you troubleshoot a service that won't start?
A common troubleshooting workflow is:
Check the service status:
systemctl status <service>
View recent logs:
journalctl -u <service> -n 50
Verify the service file:
Confirm the ExecStart path is correct.
Ensure the executable exists and has execute permission.
Test the command manually:
/path/to/executable
If the service file was changed:
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
Restart the service:
sudo systemctl restart <service>
Check for configuration errors (if supported by the service), such as:
nginx -t


